        <?php echo $this->stencil->setHeadline('Thomas E. Kurtz'); ?>
        <p><strong>Thomas Eugene Kurtz</strong> (born 22 February 1928) was a Dartmouth professor of mathematics and a computer scientist, who along with his colleague <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('John Kemeny', 'P'); ?> set in motion the then revolutionary concept of making computers as freely available to college students as library books were, by implementing the concept of Time Sharing at Dartmouth College.</p>
        <p>In his mission to allow non-expert users to interact with the computer, he co-developed the <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('BASIC', 'L'); ?> programming language (<strong>B</strong>eginners <strong>A</strong>ll-purpose <strong>S</strong>ymbolic <strong>I</strong>nstruction <strong>C</strong>ode) during 1963 to 1964.</p>
